Hi Ms. Price,
Thank you for spending your valuable weekend time to reply to our email, we really appreciate it! We were reluctant to write this email in fear of disrespecting you, however, we thought that a committed teacher like you would prefer for us to bring you our concerns.¬†

We understand how our final product lacks the fun and interest needed in a feature article. However, since the project itself was titled ‚ÄúResearch Project‚Äù and there was no mention in the instructions of the project that it was related to travel, we understood it as a research paper with the aim to inform our readers about the history and customs of the two tribes. As a result, we spent a great deal of time researching as well as cutting our essay to fit your two-page limit. We got points docked off in both the ‚ÄúVisuals‚Äù and ‚ÄúTravel Appeal‚Äù areas of the rubric. As you already gave us a 6/10 on ‚ÄúTravel Appeal‚Äù, we feel as if we were penalized twice for the same cause. 

Additionally, none of us recall seeing the rubric in class. Is it possible that you may have presented it to your 2nd-period class but not 4th? We did not know that this assignment had a rubric until you debriefed it with us in class, which was after we turned in the assignment.

Is it possible for you to regrade our project given the conditions?¬†¬†

We understand that distance learning is not ideal for communication and problems like these likely would not happen if classes were held in real life. Thank you so much for your time and consideration, especially for teaching us during these difficult times!¬†
Best,Emily, Hanni, Isabelle, Joseph
